 <methods> <methodStep> <description> <section> <title>Data on vascular plants</title>
 <para>Data on vascular plants was collected in June-July on the transect lines being located on the buffer zones and the field margins between the buffer zones and the neighboring waterways. The other semi-natural habitats were not included to the plant study. Coverages of vascular plant species were evaluated on the whole area of the 50 m long and 1 m wide lines by using a nine-class scale (1&lt;0,125 %; 2=0,125 &#8211; 0,5 %; 3=0,5 - 2 %; 4=2 &#8211; 4 %; 5=4 &#8211; 8 %; 6=8 &#8211;16 %; 7=16 &#8211; 32 %; 8=32 &#8211; 64 %; 9&gt;64 %). Additionally, coverages of plant species were evaluated per cent on two 1 x 1 m quadrates on each line. The quadrates were located so that the centre of a quadrate was at the distance of 17 m from the end of the line and 16 m from the centre of the other quadrate. In total, 84 transect lines and 168 quadrates were studied.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
 <methodStep> <description> <section> <title>Data on day-active Lepidoptera</title>
 <para>Monitoring of pollinators was carried out using the standard line-transect method (Pollard &amp; Yates 1993), in which a transect route is walked at a steady speed and all individuals within a 5 x 5 m square ahead are recorded. The counts were carried out on all the 210 transect lines seven times in May-August at approximately 2-week intervals in weather conditions allowing insect activity.</para>
 <para>Pollard, E. &amp; Yates, T. 1993. Monitoring butterflies for ecology and conservation. Chapman &amp; Hall. London, UK. 274 p.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
 <methodStep> <description> <section> <title>Environmental variables</title>
 <para>The environmental variables were divided into two groups: the variables measuring the local habitat quality on the transect line, and the variables measuring the quality of the surrounding landscape. Some of the variables were evaluated only on the transect lines where the plant data was collected, i.e. on the buffer zones and the field margins between the buffer zones and the neighboring waterways. The surrounding landscape was studied by mapping the coverages of different habitat types: fields, forests, meadow patches and other habitats within a radius of both 100 m and 500 m of the transect line of the studied buffer zone.</para>
 </section>
 </description>
 </methodStep>
